3. How do you design a REST API using FastAPI?
    Principles
    Use proper HTTP methods:
        GET → fetch
        POST → create
        PUT → update
        DELETE → remove
        Use meaningful endpoints
        Use Pydantic models for validation
        Example (real-world: Todo app)

        from fastapi import FastAPI
        from pydantic import BaseModel

        app = FastAPI()

        class Todo(BaseModel):
            title: str
            completed: bool = False

        todos = []

        @app.post("/todos")
        def create_todo(todo: Todo):
            todos.append(todo)
            return todo

        @app.get("/todos")
        def get_todos():
            return todos

        @app.put("/todos/{id}")
        def update_todo(id: int, todo: Todo):
            todos[id] = todo
            return todo

        @app.delete("/todos/{id}")
        def delete_todo(id: int):
            return {"message": "Deleted"}

        Real-world use
            Task management app
            Backend for mobile apps
            Microservices
---------------------------------------------------------
4. Explain how a GET API works in FastAPI

A GET request:
    Retrieves data
    Does NOT modify anything
    Can include query/path parameters

Example
    @app.get("/products/{product_id}")
    def get_product(product_id: int):
        return {"product_id": product_id}

How it works (step-by-step)

    Client sends request:

        GET /products/10
        FastAPI matches route
        Extracts product_id = 10
        Runs function
        Returns JSON response
        With query params
        @app.get("/search")
        def search(q: str):
            return {"query": q}

        Request:

            GET /search?q=laptop
            Real-world use
                Fetch product details in e-commerce
                Get user profile
                Retrieve analytics data
